---

<BaseLayout
  title="Fundamentals 12 — Lillian Chambers"
  description="Unfolding case study: Postoperative Assessment and Surgical Site Care (FUN-12)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/fundamentals/`}>Fundamentals</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Fundamentals 12 — Lillian Chambers</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Postoperative / GI</span>
    <h1>Fundamentals 12 — Lillian Chambers</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Postoperative Assessment After Open Appendectomy for Ruptured Appendix</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Lillian Chambers, 40 years, Korean-American Female</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the morning nurse on a surgical unit. Lillian Chambers underwent an urgent open appendectomy yesterday for a ruptured appendix. She is postoperative day 1. She is quiet and appears uncomfortable.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Lillian Chambers</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Gender</th><td>40 years · Korean-American Female</td></tr>
            <tr><th>MRN</th><td>7781324</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Ruptured appendix → urgent open appendectomy</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>Review MAR</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Post-op day</th><td>Day 1 — yesterday's emergency surgery</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Last pain med</th><td>Morphine IV 3 hours ago; pain 7/10 currently</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Postoperative Medications</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>IV Antibiotics</strong> (metronidazole + cefazolin) — peritonitis prevention</li>
          <li><strong>Morphine or Hydromorphone</strong> — IV postoperative pain management</li>
          <li><strong>Acetaminophen</strong> — IV/PO adjunct pain management</li>
          <li><strong>Ondansetron (Zofran)</strong> — IV for postoperative nausea/vomiting</li>
          <li><strong>IV Fluids</strong> (LR or NS) — fluid maintenance</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>Lillian is lying very still in bed with the head elevated at about 30°. She is pale and her face is tense. She rates her pain as 7/10 in her lower abdomen. The incentive spirometer is on the table — untouched. An abdominal dressing is visible. A Jackson-Pratt drain is in place. You notice she does not complain spontaneously — she waits to be asked.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Lillian does not volunteer pain complaints. Why might this be, and what does it mean for your care?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Cultural context — Korean-American patient:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Some patients of Korean or East Asian backgrounds may <strong>underreport pain</strong> due to cultural norms of stoicism or not wanting to burden healthcare providers</li>
          <li>The nurse should <strong>proactively assess pain</strong> using a numeric scale rather than waiting for the patient to report it</li>
          <li>Observe nonverbal cues: facial tension, guarding, limited movement, clenched teeth</li>
          <li>Frame pain questions non-judgmentally: "On a scale of 0 to 10, with 10 being the worst pain you can imagine, where is your pain right now?"</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Why pain management is urgent post-appendectomy:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Uncontrolled pain → splinting → shallow breathing → atelectasis</li>
          <li>Pain prevents deep breathing exercises (IS) and early ambulation — both critical for recovery</li>
          <li>Assess and treat pain FIRST before other interventions</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You administer analgesic and perform your systematic postoperative assessment…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Postoperative Head-to-Toe Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">After administering IV morphine, you wait 20 minutes and then proceed with your systematic postoperative assessment. Lillian's pain has decreased to 4/10.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Vital Signs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Temperature</th><td>37.9°C (100.2°F) — low-grade <span class="text-danger">(monitor)</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood Pressure</th><td>118/74 mmHg</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Heart Rate</th><td>94 bpm (mild tachycardia — pain/fever)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Respiratory Rate</th><td>20 breaths/min; shallow</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SpO₂</th><td><span class="text-danger">94% on room air</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Pain</th><td>4/10 (improved from 7/10)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🫁 Respiratory / GI Findings</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Lung sounds: crackles at bilateral bases; shallow respirations</li>
          <li>Not using incentive spirometer</li>
          <li>Bowel sounds: absent in all quadrants</li>
          <li>Abdomen: slightly distended; tender to palpation RLQ</li>
          <li>No flatus yet (expected day 1 post-op)</li>
          <li>Nausea present; no vomiting yet</li>
          <li>NPO status; IV fluids running</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Low-grade fever at 24 hours + crackles + SpO₂ 94% — what is the likely cause and intervention?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Most likely cause: Atelectasis</strong> (pulmonary collapse)</p>
        <p>Using the 5 W's of postoperative fever — fever at 24–48 hours post-op is most commonly from <strong>Wind (atelectasis)</strong>, not infection.</p>
        <p><strong>Why atelectasis develops post-appendectomy:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>General anesthesia depresses respiratory drive</li>
          <li>Pain from abdominal incision causes splinting (shallow breathing)</li>
          <li>Immobility reduces normal lung expansion</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Interventions:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Address pain first</strong> — Lillian won't breathe deeply while in pain</li>
          <li>Teach and coach incentive spirometry — 10 breaths/hour while awake</li>
          <li>Teach splinting technique — hold pillow against incision when coughing/deep breathing</li>
          <li>Reposition to High-Fowler's — maximizes lung expansion</li>
          <li>Encourage early ambulation when safe</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ With vital signs addressed, you perform the surgical site and drain assessment…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Surgical Site Care and Drain Management</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You prepare for a wound assessment and dressing change per order. Lillian has a midline lower abdominal incision from the open appendectomy and a Jackson-Pratt (JP) drain in the right lower quadrant.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩹 Wound Assessment</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Incision</th><td>Lower midline; 10 cm; staples/sutures intact</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Wound edges</th><td>Approximated — no separation</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Drainage on dressing</th><td>Scant serosanguineous — expected day 1</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Redness</th><td>Mild at incision edges — expected post-op inflammation</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Warmth</th><td>Mild warmth at site</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Odor</th><td>None</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Signs of dehiscence</th><td>None</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🔧 Jackson-Pratt (JP) Drain Assessment</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Output color</th><td>Serosanguineous (pink-red tinged)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Output amount</th><td>35 mL since midnight</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Consistency</th><td>Thin — no clots</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Drain site</th><td>Intact; no leakage around insertion site</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Bulb status</th><td>Compressed (maintaining suction) — correct</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🔄 Dressing Change Procedure</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1</td><td>Perform hand hygiene; gather supplies; explain to Lillian</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2</td><td>Remove old dressing inside-out; dispose in biohazard container</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3</td><td>Assess wound (as above) — document findings</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4</td><td>Cleanse per order (normal saline or as directed)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>5</td><td>Apply new sterile dressing per order</td></tr>
          <tr><td>6</td><td>Perform hand hygiene after completion</td></tr>
          <tr><td>7</td><td>Empty and measure JP drain; record output; re-compress bulb</td></tr>
          <tr><td>8</td><td>Document wound findings and drain output in medical record</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: When is it concerning if the JP drain output suddenly increases or changes color?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Concerning JP drain findings — notify provider:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sudden large increase in output</strong> → possible hemorrhage or anastomotic leak</li>
          <li><strong>Bright red blood</strong> → active hemorrhage</li>
          <li><strong>Purulent (green/yellow) output</strong> → wound or abdominal infection/abscess</li>
          <li><strong>Feculent (foul-smelling, brown) output</strong> → bowel anastomosis leak — EMERGENCY</li>
          <li><strong>No output but distended abdomen</strong> → drain may be occluded; fluid may be collecting internally</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>When to expect drain removal:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Output &lt; 25–30 mL in 24 hours</li>
          <li>Drainage changes from serosanguineous to serous</li>
          <li>No signs of ongoing infection or fluid collection</li>
          <li>Provider determines source of drainage has resolved</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ With wound care complete, you coach breathing exercises and assess bowel sounds…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Respiratory Care and GI Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Lillian's pain is now 3/10 after the analgesic. You coach her on incentive spirometry and assess bowel function — critical markers of recovery after abdominal surgery.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🌬️ Incentive Spirometry with Splinting</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Explain why IS is critical: "This prevents pneumonia from developing after surgery."</li>
          <li>Teach splinting: "Hold this pillow firmly against your belly while you breathe and cough — it will help reduce pain."</li>
          <li>Demonstrate: "Breathe in slowly and as deeply as you can — hold for 3 seconds — then breathe out slowly."</li>
          <li>Goal: 10 slow deep breaths per hour while awake</li>
          <li>Praise effort: "Even if it's a small breath, you're doing your lungs a favor."</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🔊 GI/Bowel Function Assessment</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Absent bowel sounds</td><td>Expected day 1 — paralytic ileus from surgery/anesthesia</td></tr>
            <tr><td>First flatus</td><td>Key sign bowel function is returning; often day 2–3</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Bowel sounds returning</td><td>Signal to consider diet advancement</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Nausea present</td><td>Expected; ondansetron ordered</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Diet progression</td><td>NPO → clear liquids → soft → regular as tolerated</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What is a paralytic ileus and how do you manage it?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Paralytic ileus</strong> is temporary cessation of normal bowel peristalsis (movement) following abdominal surgery or trauma. It is caused by:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Manipulation of the bowel during surgery</li>
          <li>General anesthesia effects</li>
          <li>Opioid medications (significantly slow GI motility)</li>
          <li>Electrolyte imbalances</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Signs:</strong> Absent bowel sounds, abdominal distension, nausea/vomiting, no flatus, failure to pass stool</p>
        <p><strong>Management:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>NPO until bowel sounds return and flatus is passed</li>
          <li>Early ambulation — walking stimulates peristalsis</li>
          <li>Chewing gum (evidence-based) — stimulates vagal nerve → promotes gut motility</li>
          <li>IV fluids for hydration</li>
          <li>Minimize opioids — use multimodal analgesia to reduce GI effects</li>
          <li>Notify provider if severe distension, vomiting, or no bowel sounds by day 3–4</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You address Lillian's cultural needs and prepare discharge teaching…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Cultural Sensitivity and Patient Teaching</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">After the breathing exercises, Lillian seems more comfortable. You sit beside her and ask how she is feeling. She says softly, "I feel embarrassed that I needed emergency surgery. I did not know I was this sick." Her family is asking to visit.</p>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do you respond therapeutically and address Korean-American cultural considerations?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Therapeutic response:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>"Ms. Chambers, a ruptured appendix is a medical emergency — it came on suddenly and you did exactly the right thing by coming to the hospital. This was not preventable."</li>
          <li>Validate her experience: "It makes sense to feel overwhelmed after such unexpected surgery."</li>
          <li>Focus on recovery: "You are doing the right things now. Each step you take today — the deep breathing, the walking — is healing you."</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Korean-American cultural considerations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Pain underreporting</strong> — proactively ask about pain; watch nonverbal cues (guarding, facial tension)</li>
          <li><strong>Respect and deference</strong> — Lillian may not ask questions directly; invite them: "What questions do you have for me?"</li>
          <li><strong>Family involvement</strong> — ask how she would like family included in care and information sharing</li>
          <li><strong>Interpreter</strong> — if English is not her first language, use professional interpreter for medical decisions (not family members)</li>
          <li><strong>Traditional practices</strong> — ask respectfully about herbal remedies or traditional health practices; some may interact with medications</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>📋 Discharge Teaching Topics (Begin Day 1)</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Topic</th><th>Key Points</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Activity</strong></td><td>Light walking as tolerated now; no heavy lifting &gt;10 lbs for 4–6 weeks; no driving on opioids</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Wound care</strong></td><td>Keep incision dry; shower (no bath/pool); signs of infection to report</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Diet</strong></td><td>Progress liquids → soft → regular; high fiber + hydration to prevent constipation</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Bowel function</strong></td><td>Stool softeners with opioids; report no BM by day 3</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Return precautions</strong></td><td>Fever &gt;101°F, increasing abdominal pain/rigidity, wound opening, inability to keep fluids down</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You complete your nursing diagnoses and documentation…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Priority Nursing Diagnoses and Documentation</h2>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Acute Pain</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Pain 7/10 (then 4/10 post-analgesic); guarding; facial tension; limited movement; splinting breathing</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Infection</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Ruptured appendix (peritonitis risk); surgical incision; IV antibiotics in progress</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Ineffective Breathing Pattern</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: SpO₂ 94%; RR 20 shallow; crackles bilateral bases; low-grade fever; not using IS</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Constipation</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Opioid use; NPO status; post-surgical ileus; absent bowel sounds</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">5</span>
        <div><strong>Deficient Knowledge</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Unexpected emergency surgery; needs postoperative care education and discharge planning</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling Provider About Lillian's Respiratory Status</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>Calling about Lillian Chambers, post-op day 1 following urgent open appendectomy for ruptured appendix, with SpO₂ of 94% and low-grade fever of 100.2°F.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>40-year-old Korean-American female. Emergency surgery yesterday. On IV antibiotics (metronidazole + cefazolin), morphine, acetaminophen, ondansetron, and IV fluids. JP drain in place; output 35 mL serosanguineous since midnight.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>Pain improved to 4/10 after morphine. SpO₂ 94%; crackles at bilateral bases; was not using incentive spirometer due to pain. Bowel sounds absent; no flatus yet — consistent with expected post-op ileus day 1. Abdominal wound intact; dressing changed; wound edges approximated with no dehiscence.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting: review of pain management plan; order to titrate O₂ if needed; confirm antibiotic course timing; anticipated diet advancement order when bowel sounds return.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Metronidazole IV</strong></td><td>Antibiotic (anaerobic coverage)</td><td>Treats anaerobic bacteria from GI perforation; infuse over 30–60 min; metallic taste; avoid alcohol; may cause nausea</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Cefazolin IV</strong></td><td>First-generation cephalosporin</td><td>Gram-positive and some gram-negative coverage; assess for penicillin allergy cross-reactivity; monitor renal function</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Morphine IV</strong></td><td>Opioid analgesic</td><td>HIGH ALERT; monitor RR (hold if &lt;12); sedation level; constipation risk; naloxone available; assess pain 30 min after</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Ondansetron (Zofran)</strong></td><td>5-HT3 antagonist antiemetic</td><td>For PONV (postoperative nausea and vomiting); monitor QT interval; IV push over ≥ 30 seconds; headache is common side effect</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Acetaminophen IV/PO</strong></td><td>Non-opioid analgesic</td><td>Opioid-sparing; max 4 g/day from ALL sources; assess liver function; give scheduled (not just PRN) for better postop pain control</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: What are the complications of a ruptured appendix and open appendectomy?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Complication</th><th>Key Signs</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Wound infection</td><td>Redness, warmth, purulent drainage, fever &gt;72 hrs post-op</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Peritonitis</td><td>Rebound tenderness, rigid abdomen, fever, tachycardia</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Paralytic ileus</td><td>Absent bowel sounds, distension, nausea, no flatus</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Atelectasis/Pneumonia</td><td>Fever at 24–48 hrs, crackles, decreased SpO₂</td></tr>
            <tr><td>DVT / PE</td><td>Calf pain/swelling; sudden dyspnea (PE)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Abscess formation</td><td>Persistent fever after 72 hrs, RLQ pain</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Wound dehiscence</td><td>Wound edges separating; "popping" sensation</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sepsis</td><td>Fever/hypothermia, tachycardia, hypotension, altered mentation</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: How is return of bowel function assessed postoperatively?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Auscultate bowel sounds</strong> — presence in all 4 quadrants indicates returning peristalsis</li>
          <li>Ask about <strong>passage of flatus</strong> — first sign of bowel function returning</li>
          <li>Monitor for <strong>nausea, vomiting, abdominal distension</strong></li>
          <li>Monitor <strong>diet tolerance</strong> — advance from clear liquids to solid food as tolerated</li>
          <li>Absent bowel sounds + distension + nausea = <strong>paralytic ileus</strong> — hold oral intake; notify provider</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What are the cultural considerations for Lillian as a Korean-American patient?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>May underreport pain due to cultural stoicism — proactively assess using numeric scale</li>
          <li>May not ask questions directly — invite them: "What questions do you have for me?"</li>
          <li>Family involvement in decisions may be important — ask how she would like family included</li>
          <li>Use professional interpreter for medical decisions if English is limited — never use family as medical interpreter</li>
          <li>Ask about traditional health practices/herbal remedies that may interact with medications</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What is the splinting technique and why is it important?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Splinting:</strong> Holding a pillow firmly against an abdominal or thoracic incision when coughing, deep breathing, or sneezing.</p>
        <p><strong>Why it helps:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Reduces movement and stretch at the incision site → reduces pain</li>
          <li>Reduced pain allows for deeper, more effective breaths and coughs</li>
          <li>Protects incision from dehiscence with the force of coughing</li>
          <li>Promotes patient willingness to participate in respiratory care</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What patient-reported symptom signals the best return of bowel function?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Passage of flatus (gas).</strong> This is the most reliable early indicator that peristalsis is returning after surgery. It is asked about directly: "Have you passed any gas?" Once flatus is passed, diet advancement from NPO/clear liquids can typically begin.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

